<p>
  Hi <%= @user.first_name %>,
</p>

<p>
  You've uploaded your project and seen the price, nice work! If the number
  came out higher than you'd hoped, the good news is you have a lot of control
  over it. These are the three settings that move the price the most:
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Resolution</strong><br>
  Render time scales roughly quadratically with resolution, so doubling the
  resolution can roughly quadruple the price. Dropping from 4K to 1080p makes a
  big difference.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Cycles samples</strong><br>
  The price scales roughly linearly with samples: halving the samples roughly
  halves the price. With Blender's denoiser you can often go lower than you'd
  expect without losing much quality.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Render time / deadline</strong><br>
  The tighter your deadline, the more servers we need, so the more it costs. If
  you can allow a little more time, we can use our cheapest data centers and
  keep the price low. A tight deadline may push us to pricier servers and spike
  the cost more quickly.
</p>

<p>
  Tweak any of these and recalculate to see the new price instantly. You can
  also check the preview renders on the project page to confirm quality before
  you commit. When it looks right, hit render:
</p>

<p>
  <a href="<%= projects_url(session_token: @session_token) %>"
     style="display: inline-block; padding: 12px 22px; background: #101828;
            color: #ffffff; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 6px;
            font-weight: bold;">
    Open your project
  </a>
</p>

<p>
  Questions about any of this? Just hit reply.
</p>

<p>
  Happy rendering,<br>
  the Blendergrid team
</p>

<p>
  <a href="https://www.blendergrid.com">www.blendergrid.com</a>
</p>
